column2: intensely colored artworks
column3: but his penchant for being proprietary has long irked others in the art world. But then came Vantablack. Earlier this year
column4: Kapoor sparked outrage from artists all over the world with the announcement that he had made a deal to become the only person in the world allowed to use the blackest pigment of black paint ever developed. Known as Vantablack
column5: the unique carbon nanotube-based pigment is produced solely by a British company called NanoSystem
column6: and was originally developed for military technologies. However
column7: Kapoor made an agreement with the company that he is the only person allowed to use it for artistic purposes. Needless to say
column8: that made plenty of other artists furious. ‚ÄúWhen I first heard that Anish had the exclusive rights to the blackest black I was really disappointed
column9: ‚Äù artist Stuart Semple tells Kevin Holmes for The Creators Project. ‚ÄúI was desperate to have a play with it in my own work and I knew lots of other artists who wanted to use it too. It just seemed really mean-spirited and against the spirit of generosity that most artists who make and share their work are driven by.‚Äù Like Kapoor
column10: Semple‚Äôs work often uses vivid shades of color
column11: and for years he had worked with scientists to develop increasingly intense pigments to use in his artwork. So as a response to Kapoor‚Äôs exclusive deal with Vantablack
column12: Semple decided to release his own special pigment
column14: ‚Äù the Irish Examiner reports.  While ‚ÄúPink‚Äù isn‚Äôt based on nanotechnology
column16: Semple says it is the pinkest pink pigment ever created. Now
column17: in an effort to thumb his nose at Kapoor
column18: Semple is making it for sale to everyone in the world‚Äîexcept Kapoor
